                    <span>I thought the book was interesting, but I was not captured by it. I found it even a little boring.  I bought the book, because I thought Veronica Haddon and Mark Haddon were related, but I was wrong.  I loved Whispers of the wicked saints, but I can not recomend this book.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A Delivery Device for the Author's 'Neat Thoughts'</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-06</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The story of this book is actually pretty cool! I like the whole dog-murder-mystery thing, it was a very neat idea.
<br />
<br />Unfortunately, this little bit of story is only filler, used in-between the author's little siderants about reality and science.  It's cool, I guess any way to get a lot of people exposed to science and philosophical ideas is neat...but it's so forced that I found it a bit painful :(
<br />
<br />I think it's most interesting how the author chose to deliver these spiffy thoughts of his, though. An autistic character is a clever background reason to go off on 'smart' tangents.  If only they were just-as-cleverly integrated into the story, instead of just scattering a story around them.
<br />
<br />Good book I guess, if you're into that sorta thing.</span>
                  
              
